The South Asian COVID-19 situation, according to data from Worldometer (https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/) as of 13 Aug 2021 at 07:10 GMT:
Country: Total cases / Total deaths / Deaths per million population
India: 32 117 826 / 430 285 / 308
Bangladesh: 1 396 868 / 23 613/ 142
Pakistan: 1 089 913 / 24 266 / 108
Nepal: 725 769 / 10 212 / 344
Sri Lanka: 345 118 / 5620 / 261
Afghanistan: 151 770 / 7000 / 175
Maldives: 78 815 / 222 / 403
Bhutan: 2553 / 3 / 4

Over the last 7 days, 261 069, 74 214, 31 508, 17 690, 23 689, and 1964 COVID-19 cases were detected in India, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Nepal, Sri Lanka, and Afghanistan, respectively, compared with 284 413, 96 401, 33 544, 17 437, 17 227, and 3283 in the preceding 7 days, revealing a slowly decreasing trend in India, a decreasing trend for the 1st time in Bangladesh since the new peak started building up from the beginning of last month (July 2021), almost a stable trend in Pakistan and Nepal, a decreasing trend in Afghanistan, but the continuation of the development of a sharp peak of new cases in Sri Lanka.

Live Situational Analysis on COVID-19 cases in Sri Lanka can be seen at https://hpb.health.gov.lk/covid19-dashboard/. For the 1st time, the number of daily deaths in Sri Lanka attributed to the disease crossed the mark of 100, and such a death trend continued for
the last 3 consecutive days. The situation would aggravate further due to the spread of the delta variant in the country.

It is hard to comment whether or not the new wave in Pakistan has reached its peak because we are seeing a kind of stability of new cases over a period of just 7 days. Because the delta variant of the virus is active in the country, the possibility of seeing a reverse trend in the next week or so cannot be ruled out.

The current proportional case positivity is much higher in Bangladesh compared to other South Asian countries. Although the daily case positivity dropped to around 23% from the highest positivity of around 32% seen in the current peak, the country has withdrawn the strict lockdown measures imposed for 19 days in total with a recession of 7 days to celebrate Eid-ul-Adha ("Festival of Sacrifice").

The government has decided to lift most of the restrictions from 19 Aug 2021 despite a prevailing case positivity of around 23% and daily deaths of over 200 (https://www.thedailystar.net/news/bangladesh/governance/news/everything-open-aug-19-2151036.

The beginning of an increasing trend again cannot be ruled out due to this relaxation.

The total number of deaths in Nepal attributed to the disease has crossed the milestone of 10 000, and 7000 in Afghanistan.

To compare the situation in South Asian countries above with previous disease data, ProMED-SoAs readers are referred to the archives below:
